# Centralized vs Distributed Version Control

## Introduction

Version Control Systems (VCS) help developers track changes in projects. Among the different types of VCS, the two most commonly used are:

- Centralized Version Control System (CVCS)
- Distributed Version Control System (DVCS)

Understanding the difference between these two systems is important because **SVN** follows the centralized model, while **Git** follows the distributed model.

---

# Centralized Version Control System (CVCS)

A **Centralized Version Control System (CVCS)** stores the project's source code and history on a **single central server**.

Every developer connects to this central server to download files, upload changes, and collaborate with the team.

```
            Central Server
                 │
     ┌───────────┼───────────┐
     │           │           │
Developer A  Developer B  Developer C
```

The server acts as the single source of truth. If you want the latest version of the project, you must connect to the server.

---

## How CVCS Works

1. A central server stores the complete project.
2. Developers download the latest version.
3. They make changes on their local computers.
4. The changes are sent back to the central server.
5. Other developers update their local copies from the server.

---

## Advantages of CVCS

- Easy to understand and manage.
- One central location for the project.
- Better control over user permissions.
- Simple project administration.
- Everyone works on the same central repository.

---

## Disadvantages of CVCS

- Requires access to the central server.
- Internet or network connection is usually needed.
- If the server crashes, development may stop.
- Single point of failure.
- Limited offline work.

---

## Examples of CVCS

- Apache Subversion (SVN)
- CVS (Concurrent Versions System)
- Perforce (uses a centralized model)

---

# Distributed Version Control System (DVCS)

A **Distributed Version Control System (DVCS)** gives every developer a **complete copy of the repository**, including the entire project history.

Developers do not depend on a central server for most operations.

```
Developer A
Complete Repository
        │
        │
Developer B
Complete Repository
        │
        │
Developer C
Complete Repository

        ↕ Synchronization

   Remote Repository (GitHub)
```

Each developer has their own complete repository.

---

## How DVCS Works

1. Clone the repository.
2. Receive the complete project history.
3. Work locally.
4. Save changes using commits.
5. Push changes to the remote repository.
6. Other developers pull the latest updates.

---

## Advantages of DVCS

- Works offline.
- Faster operations.
- Complete project history on every computer.
- Better backup.
- No single point of failure.
- Easier branching and merging.
- Excellent collaboration.

---

## Disadvantages of DVCS

- Slightly more storage required.
- More concepts for beginners.
- Synchronization may require additional commands.

---

## Examples of DVCS

- Git
- Mercurial
- Bazaar

